---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Eyebrow from "../components/Eyebrow.astro";
import Button from "../components/Button.astro";

const title = "Philosophy — Arachne";
const description =
  "Why some judgments stay with a person, why declared process beats a runtime trace, and the gap Arachne exists to close.";
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} editorial={true}>
  <section class="section philosophy">
    <div class="container measure-narrow prose">
      <Eyebrow>Philosophy</Eyebrow>
      <h1>What a model can do, and what stays with a person.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Organizations already know how to do most of their work. The open
        question is which parts can be written down, which parts can be handed
        to a machine, and which parts must remain answerable to a human. These
        are the lines Arachne is built around.
      </p>

      <h2>Not all judgment is delegable to AI</h2>
      <p>
        Accountability is not transferable. When a consequential decision turns
        out to be wrong, someone is answerable for it, and that responsibility
        cannot be handed to a model. The model produces an output; it does not
        absorb the consequence.
      </p>
      <p>
        Arachne routes the non-delegable judgments to a person rather than
        pretending they were automated. A flow does not quietly fold a decision
        that someone will have to answer for into a step labelled as machine
        work.
      </p>

      <h2>Process and discretion are both real</h2>
      <p>
        Institutions run on standardized process and on delegated discretion.
        The standard part — the repeatable, specifiable part — can be
        formalized. The discretion part runs on human trust networks:
        reputations, relationships, the knowledge of who is accountable to whom.
      </p>
      <p>
        An AI cannot join those networks. A tool that ignores them models only
        half of how an organization actually works, and the missing half is the
        half that decides what happens when the standard case does not apply.
      </p>

      <h2>Trust is checking placed on purpose</h2>
      <p>
        Being able to check an output after the fact does not, by itself, make a
        process trustworthy. Trust also requires knowing the process is stable,
        owned, and the same tomorrow as it was today.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each step does a narrow job with only the information it needs, which is
        what makes checking it quick rather than a second full reading. Trust
        need not rest on any one step; it rests on the whole, laid out where you
        can read it.
      </p>
      <p>
        The point of automation is not to check less for its own sake, but to
        check where checking earns its keep. A system you must audit output by
        output has not automated the work — it has moved the labor from doing to
        reviewing. A system you never check is not trustworthy either; it is just
        unexamined. The goal is to put checking where it belongs and remove it
        where it no longer does.
      </p>
      <p>
        A declared flow lets you place it deliberately. You stop at a Gate where
        a judgment is yours to make. You trace a wrong result back through
        provenance to the step that produced it. And as each fix improves the
        process, the checks you needed early fall away — you converge on
        inspecting only what genuinely cannot be delegated. A runtime trace of
        an agent's improvisation gives you none of this: it tells you what
        happened once, not what will happen again, so it leaves you checking
        everything, every time.
      </p>

      <h2>Data control is architectural, not a policy</h2>
      <p>
        A promise not to look at your data is weaker than a system where the
        data never leaves infrastructure you control. Ownership that depends on
        a vendor's good behavior is not ownership.
      </p>
      <p>
        Sensitive fields can be redacted or blinded before anything reaches a
        model. Low-stakes inference can run on local models. Where the data goes
        is a property of how the system is built, not a clause you are asked to
        trust.
      </p>

      <h2>Errors should fix the process, not patch the case</h2>
      <p>
        Organizations that function well do not blame individuals. They fix the
        process so the mistake cannot recur. The repair outlives the incident.
      </p>
      <p>
        When the process is a declared flow, the fix is a visible, testable,
        versioned change — not an edit to a prompt you cannot fully see and
        cannot reliably reproduce. The model does not have to get better for the
        work to. The process does — and the process is the part you own.
      </p>

      <h2>Ad-hoc AI use is not organizational process</h2>
      <p>
        Pasting content into a chat window encodes individual interactions, not
        process. The history lives in one person's account and leaves when they
        do. There is no artifact that says: this is how we do this.
      </p>
      <p>
        Crossing from the first to the second — from a private habit to a stated
        process the organization can read, test, and own — is the gap Arachne
        exists to close.
      </p>

      <p class="onward">
        <Button href="/blog" variant="ghost">Read the blog</Button>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .prose {
    font-family: var(--font-editorial);
  }

  .prose h1 {
    margin-top: var(--s-16);
    max-width: 24ch;
  }

  .prose .lead {
    margin-top: var(--s-24);
    color: var(--fg-1);
  }

  .prose h2 {
    margin-top: var(--s-40);
    max-width: 30ch;
  }

  .prose p {
    margin-top: var(--s-16);
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--fg-1);
  }

  .prose .lead {
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .onward {
    margin-top: var(--s-40);
  }
</style>
